1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 dxc4 5. a4 Bf5 6. Nh4
{ This is the 3rd move in popularity by quite some margin. White does not focus on regaining the c4-pawn immediately, but directly starts challenging Black's bishop on f5. Black now has many different tries - often he just returns the bishop back to c8, which gives White what he wants - but at the same time, the h4-knight looks kind of silly there and will eventually have to go back to f3. }
*

