[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 dxc4 5. a4 e6
{ This chapter focuses on Black's alternatives to 5... Bf5. Most puzzles in this chapter were taken from the variations 5... e6 and 5... Bg4. At the end there are also some tactics from the rare variations 5... Na6 and 5... a5.   5...e6  is not as bad as it looks, but it definitely isn't in the spirit of the Slav Defense. Play usually resembles the Queen's Gambit Accepted with White often getting an isolated d4-pawn.   5...Bg4  is the Steiner variation. White is more or less obliged to play  6.Ne5  , after which play resembles the  5...Bf5  6.Ne5  variation  (chapter 2)  (.)   5...Na6  , the Smyslov variation, sees Black immediately start trying to exploit the b4-square. Play seems to be similar to the mainline Dutch variation  (chapter 1)  (.)   Finally, with  5...a5  Black also looks to immediately clamp down on  b4  . }
*

