[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 dxc4 5. e4
{ This chapter is focused on White's alternatives on the 5th move, 5. e4 and 5. e3.   5.e4  This is also known as the Geller Gambit. White immediately establishes a strong center, but he can forget about regaining the c4-pawn anytime soon. Objectively White's compensation for the pawn does not seem entirely sufficient, but play often becomes very sharp - thus leading to some nice and instructive miniatures.   5.e3   This is more modest but not necessarily stronger than the Geller Gambit. It is well known that Black achieves good play after  5...b5  , even if he usually has to give back the pawn. Quite simply, there is a reason that  a4  is played more than 20 times as often as  e4  and  e3  on the 5th move. }
*

