1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 a6 5. c5
{ Since 4... a6 weakened the dark squares on the queenside, this reply immediately tries to take advantage of that  (and grab some space in the process)  . Of course 5. c5 also has its downsides - the tension in the center has been released early, which means Black won't have to worry about his d5-pawn in the near future, and Black can chip away at White's pawn structure by undermining the d4-pawn with ...e5 or attack the head of the pawn chain with ...b6. }
*

