[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. c4 c6 4. Nc3 a6 5. c5 Nbd7 6. Qc2 Qc7 7. e4 Nxe4 8. Nxe4
dxe4 9. Ng5 Nf6 10. Bc4 Nd5 11. Qxe4 h6 12. Nf3 Be6 13. Qe2 Bg4 14. h3 Bxf3 15.
Qxf3 Rd8 16. O-O g6 17. Re1 Bg7 18. Bxd5 Rxd5 19. Bf4 Qd7 20. Bd6 Rf5 21. Rxe7+
{ It takes great foresight to sacrifice the rook this way ! } 21... Qxe7 22.
Qb3
{ The point is that Black has to either let go of b7, through which the white queen can enter decisively, or let go of the e-file which allows the remaining white rook to enter the attack.    Wrong is  22.Qc3?  Qd8  23.Re1+  Kd7  because White has no attack after  24.Re7+  Qxe7!  25.Bxe7  Kxe7  . }
22... Qe4
{ 22...Qd7  23.Re1+  Kd8   The computer already wants to give back a piece with  23...Be5  24.dxe5  24.Qb6+  Kc8  25.Qa7!  and White wins. }
23. Qxb7 Bf6 24. d5
{ Another clever move: White forces black to take with his queen as otherwise c6 drops  (or White's c5-pawn becomes a passed monster)  , but then he can play Re1+ with a winning attack. }
*

