[White "8. 4... a6 Slav: other moves"]
[Black "4... a6 Slav: other moves intro"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 a6 5. a4
{ This chapter deals with  (most of)   White's other replies to  a6  . It starts with  5.a4  , which is a clear attempt to counter Black's plan of playing  ...dxc4  followed by  ...b5  (as well as the immediate ...b5)  (. At the same time this move weakens White's queenside though, in particular the a5-e1 diagonal and the b4-square.)   5.Ne5  is another less popular attempt. This move directly defends White's c-pawn and makes it hard for Black to advance  ..b5  in view of the weakness of the c6-pawn. However, the knight is easily challenged by the immediate  5...Nbd7  .   5.g3  leads to Slav-Catalan hybrid positions which objectively can't promise White an advantage, but lead to original positions which not every Slav player will be comfortable with.   5.cxd5  finally will lead to Exchange Slav positions in which Black is already committed to a7-a6 - which is not at all a bad move, but maybe he would've liked to play something else in that variation. }
*

