[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "10. 4. Qc2 g6"]
[Black "4. Qc2 g6 intro"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Qc2 g6
{ This is the main alternative to  4...dxc4  . Black keeps the tension, prepares the development of his dark-squared bishop to  g7  , and also makes possible the development of his light-squared bishop to  f5  , challenging the white queen.  Because the tension is maintained, the pawn structure is still undefined. White can choose to keep the tension, exchange on  d5  , or push the pawn to  c5  at some point. What also may happen is that Black plays  ...Bf5  Qb3  Qb6  and then White plays  c5!  more or less forcing Black to take on  b3  , with a pawn structure that is favorable for White  (due to the open a-file)  (.) }
*

