[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "11. Exchange Slav"]
[Black "Exchange Slav intro"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. cxd5 cxd5
{ Of course no book on the Slav is complete without dealing with the dreaded exchange variation! While working on this chapter I came to two conclusions. First of all, neither side can afford to be careless in how they develop, because there are quite a few miniatures to be found in this variation.   Secondly, a lot of the tactics are fairly simple  (at least compared to the rest of the book.)  This can be for two reasons - firstly, psychologically a lot of chess players who play this variation may think 'oh it's just the exchange variation, must be an easy draw.', so they become lazy and fall victim to a simple tactic. Secondly, the position is fairly static, with a symmetrical pawn structure, one open line  (the c-file)  and limited weaknesses to exploit  (mostly the queenside pawns and the a4-e8 and a5-e1 diagonals respectively)  . }
*

[Event "?"]
